extends _base.pug

block headline
	| PhotoSYNTH Presentation

block tagline 
	| Give a Man a record and they dance for day, give that man a synthesiser and they dance for a lifetime

block main 
	.reveal
		.slides

			section
				figure.wallpaper
					img(src="/static/talk/free-parking.jpg")
				aside.notes.
					Free parking!
  
			//- section
			//- 	h1.r-fit-text _PhotoSynth 4D_

			section(style="--lines: 6;")
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/Blue Ramsey.png")
					figcaption
						p Dedicated to Blue Ramsey 1972-2024
						small.
							Who introduced me to the Fourier Transform in the 1990s
							<br> 
							and who believed in me when nobody else did. 
							Rest in peace 
					aside.notes.
						Mankind loves music,
			
			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/flute.jpg")
					figcaption
						small Divje babe Flute © Humans ~60,000 years ago 

				aside.notes
					p The flute predates the wheel by some 39 thousand years.

					p So it's clear that expressing ourselves is more necessary than getting about.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/wheel.png")
					figcaption
						small The Wheel © Humans ~5,500 years ago
				aside.notes
					p Music was more important than movement.

					p Some people say that the wheel is the most important invention of all time, but if that was the case, why did it take another 39 thousand more years?

			section
				h3 MOUTHS > LEGS
				h3.fragment FLUTE > WHEEL
				h3.fragment SYNTHESISER > FLUTE
				
				aside.notes
					p Clearly people were happy with their flutes. 

					strong [CLICK]

					p In 2026 we have more than flutes to choose from... we have synthesisers!

					strong [CLICK]

					p and you know what they say,

			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text Give a man a record and they dance for the day,<br> give a man a synthesiser and they dance for a lifetime.
				
				aside.notes.
					Give a man a record and they dance for the day,
					But give that man a synthesiser and they  dance for a lifetime.

			section
				h3 MOUTHS > LEGS
				h3 FLUTE > WHEEL
				h3 SYNTHESISER > FLUTE
				h3 ??? > SYNTHESISER

				aside.notes.
					Of course, the ability to create infinite sounds brings with it a requirement for infinite controls!
	
			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/modular.png")
					figcaption
						small With infinite sounds come infinite controls
			
				aside.notes
					p Today, there are thousands of amazing musical instruments, but most of them are very difficult to use, confusing to play, and make lots of assumptions about the people playing them.

					p Rather than making things easier, in many ways, technology has made them more challenging.

					p So how did we get here?

			// AUDIO AUTOMATION HISTORY --------------
			section
				h3.r-fit-text A Brief History of Audio Automation

				aside.notes
					p Before music could be recorded, to hear music, you would have to play it yourself or find somebody to play it for you. 

					p You could sing or play an instrument. 

					p The best music was made together by groups - collectives of individuals performing together. 

			section
				h3.r-fit-text Orkhēstra
				aside.notes
					p Orchestras were named after the word for the dedicated room in ancient Greece for dancing to music.

					p Choirs and orchestras sounded bigger and more powerful than individuals alone.

					p Played together, sounds complement each other. 

			section 
				figure 	
					img(src="/static/talk/constructive-coherance.jpg")
					figcaption 
						small Constructive coherence.

				aside.notes
					p Constructive coherence.
			
					p The quantity of new musical instruments grew to cover all the different pitch and timbre combinations. 

					p Orchestras grew exponentially.

					p Soon, musical instruments became as expressive as singing.

					p And the complexity to play them grew to represent this broad musical range.

					p Complexity bred discontent.

					p And so, for as long as we have been making music with instruments, we have been trying to find ways to automate the process. 
				
			section 
				video( data-autoplay, muted, src="/static/talk/piano-roll.mp4").full-size.wallpaper.woodblock 
				aside.notes
					p There were church organs that used piano-rolls - punch cards with holes cut out in sequences to play the corresponding notes on the organ, or the church bell sequencer…

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/Bell Sequencer at Spielklock museum in Uterecht.png")
					figcaption
						small Bell Sequencer at Spielklock museum in Utrecht
				aside.notes
					p That operated in the much same way as the music box, triggered by pegs running round a roller 

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/carillion in the Belfort of Gent.png")
					figcaption
						small Carillon Music Box at the Belfort of Gent
				aside.notes
					p As they rotate, they twang in a musical sequence. 

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/music-box.png")
					figcaption
						small Portable Music Box at The Musical Museum, London
				aside.notes
					p These innovations led to the iPod of its day -- the portable music box. 
					
					p Finally music could be transported easily. 

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/edelweiss-turntable.png")
					figcaption
						small Edelweiss Glide, "Note plate" punch-hole turntable at The Musical Museum

				aside.notes
					p The invention of the musical disc, a platter with note holes, was clearly the precursor to the Gramophone record, 
					
					p but unlike the record, these "note plates" only contained note data - separating the performer from the performance and the data from the dance.

				
			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/El flautista.png")
					figcaption
						small Jacques de Vaucanson's El Flautista Automaton

				aside.notes
					p Inventors rushed to create self-playing musical instruments and automatons, including the inventor of the robot, Jacques de Vaucanson who made a humanoid flautist in 1737.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/dulcimer player.png")
					figcaption
						small Joseph Möllinger's The Dulcimer Player Automaton

				aside.notes
					p As time passed, more instruments were created that could replace musicians, with varying levels of complexity. 

			//- section
			//- 	figure
			//- 		img(src="/static/talk/hammond.png")
			//- 		figcaption
			//- 			small Hammond organ
			//- 	aside.notes.
				
			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/Antique Grotrian-Steinweg piano engraving.png")
					figcaption
						small Grotrian-Steinweg piano

				aside.notes
					p A punchcard keyboard to replace an organist 
			
			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/RCA MK2.png")
					figcaption
						small The first synthesiser - RCA MK2

				aside.notes
					p A synthesiser instead of a bassist,

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/tr808.jpg")
					figcaption
						small Roland TR808 Drum Machine

				aside.notes
					p A drum machine to replace the drummer,

					p It seemed the only thing that human ingenuity couldn’t replicate was the human voice itself.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/VC3.png")
					figcaption
						small Peter Zinovieff's EMS VC3 portable sequencer

				aside.notes
					p Soon note automation, otherwise known as sequencing, became the heart of the music production studio.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/heartbeat.png")
					figcaption
						small Click track is the heartbeat of the song

				aside.notes
					p What started life as the metronome, soon evolved into the electronic heartbeat known as the ‘click track’, a way of controlling other instruments so that they play in time with each other. 

			section
				figure
					//- img(src="/static/talk/MBO.png")
					video(data-autoplay, muted, src="/static/talk/graham-dunning-turntable-sequencer.mp4").full-size.wallpaper.monochromatic
			
					figcaption
						small Graham Dunning's Turntable sequencer with mechanically geared rhythm patterns 
						
				aside.notes
					p Through automation came synchronisation - keeping all instruments perfectly in time.

					p As more parts of the music could be automated, fewer people were needed to make the music, so band sizes began to shrink, but more bands formed as a result, even solo artists were now a possibility!

					p Bands went from large orchestras with dozens of different instruments or choirs with hundreds of members, to smaller collectives assisted with technology.
						
			section
				figure
					video(data-autoplay, muted, src="/static/talk/graham-dunning-digital-turntable-sequencer.mp4").full-size.wallpaper.monochromatic

					figcaption
						small Graham Dunning's Turntable sequencer with digital outputs

				aside.notes
					p So, machines revolutionised the process of making music as they not only had a fidelity and timing that most humans could only dream of, but they were reliable and very rarely made mistakes.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/reel-to-reel.jpg")
					figcaption
						small Reel to Reel Audio Recording
						
				aside.notes
					p With the advent of recorded music, which was a way to make music once, but be able to listen to it forever.

					p A single person, given time, could create music with many instruments by overlaying takes - superimposing layers of sounds on top of one another like a musical viennetta.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/amiga-music.jpg")
					figcaption
						small Personal Computing allowed people to make music at home
				aside.notes
					p With the advent of home computing, 
					p Finally
					p Pop music could be made at home... and it could be made cheap.


			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/electronium.png")
					figcaption
						small Raymond Scott's Electronium
				aside.notes
					p The idea of offsetting a complicated and unforgiving process to a machine to handle on its own, is a liberating concept, and having a competent backing band at your command is certainly convenient. 

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/dx7.png")
					figcaption
						small Yamaha DX7 FM Synthesiser
				aside.notes
					p For many decades, Popular music was defined by the sounds of the tool that made the music. To replicate the distinct sound of 1980s music, use 1980s technologies.

					p Everything would change forever however with the advent of digital signal processing, where every single nuance of a sound could be altered without a loss in quality. 

			section
				figure
					//- img(src="/static/talk/reaper-piano-roll.png").monochromatic
					img(src="/static/talk/reaper-piano-roll.png").monochromatic
					figcaption
						small Piano roll in modern Audio Workstation

				aside.notes
					p Audio could now be manipulated at the atomic level.

					p Music had been symbolically upgraded into a programming language.

			section
				figure
					//- img(src="/static/talk/reaper-piano-roll.png").monochromatic
					img(src="/static/talk/reaper-piano-roll.png").monochromatic
					figcaption
						small Piano roll in modern Audio Workstation
				
				aside.notes

					// TODO MELODYNE										
					p For example, automation could “correct” imperfections, such as altering a recording so that the singer was always in tune and in-time.

					p At first these systems were slow and large but today they work in real time and on devices that fit into your smallest pocket. 

					p The tools of today allow you to dynamically create or synthesise any sound or set of sounds without any musical background. 

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/midi-protocol.jpg")
					figcaption MIDI 1.0 Protocol

				aside.notes
					p Automation, or automatic orchestration, meant perfect replication. 

					p The click track automated tempo, digital interfaces like MIDI automated the melodies, then sampling came along and automated the timbres, the very sounds of the instruments themselves.

			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/s2000.png")
					figcaption
						small AKAI S2000 Sampler
			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/sp1200.jpg")
					figcaption
						small SP1200 Sampler

				aside.notes
					p Reliable, always available and convenient, the machines didn’t require paying and in many ways formed the perfect band.

					p A human could program instruments to play by themselves and form a whole band without people.

					p Now, in 2026, instruments can program themselves. 
				
					p Artificial intelligence is commonplace.
					
					p And devices that can generate music are not unusual.

					p But like asking ChatGPT to write you a story, 

					p It removes the process entirely and reduces your connection with the creation. 
					
					p You remain a passive consumer rather than an active creator.

			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text The real destination is the journey
				aside.notes.
					And with music making, “The real destination is the journey”.

			section
				h3 MOUTHS > LEGS
				h3 FLUTE > WHEEL
				h3 SYNTHESISER > FLUTE
				h3 ??? > SYNTHESISER
				h3.fragment CREATING > CONSUMING
				aside.notes
					p True joy comes from the act of creation, the personal expression, the feelings of representation, ownership, and the ability to share that finished piece with your friends.

					strong [CLICK]

					p With music, the end result is your prize for participation, something that holds a deep personal connection.

					p You have invested your time and expression and converted it into something that perfectly encapsulates its soul. 

					// TODO:

					p Music is kind of like an infinitely rewarding video game with unlimited levels, no high score and a satisfying prize for everybody at the end.
			
			section 
				figure 
					img(src="/static/talk/string-quartet.jpg")
					figcaption
						small String Quartet with Violin, Viola, Cello

				aside.notes
					p Instruments are designed to play together so their sonic outputs need to harmonise and sound complementary to one another. 

					p The cello improves the sound of the violin, which expands on the sound of the viola for example. 

					p These instruments speak the same language.

					p In fact all instruments speak a similar language.

			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text You’re limited by your language, by your vocabulary. You think with your language, so your language dictates how you think. But when you’re making music, it doesn’t. That’s why I love making music so much.
					cite Richard D James

				aside.notes
					p Music is just patterns of air.

					p Whether ingrained or part of a learned musical lexicon- the rules for music are firmly established and can be quantified, defined and synthesised.

					p A happy song can be written with major chords which sound elevating and uplifting, whereas a sad song can be written using a minor scale that gives it an air of melancholy and malaise.

					p Choirs around the world harmonise together without worrying about tuning or scales.

					p Instruments were created to replicate these tones and thus a common musical language naturally emerged.

					p It appears that periodicity is a characteristic of all phenomena of nature.


			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text Music is an unconscious exercise in metaphysics in which the mind is unaware that it is philosophising.

					cite Arthur Schopenhauer

				aside.notes
					p Whether or not this language is entirely intrinsic is debated, but certainly elements are universal, such as the common sounds of mumese, the language we employ to speak to babies or cute animals.

					p We automatically raise our pitch and speak softly when communicating with babies and small animals. as we expect that is how they sound. 

					p In the same way that birds didn’t go to school to learn how to sing, mumese appears to be a birthright, an intrinsic universal communication system - all built in, ready to go. 

					p Instincts.

					p Babies bounced in patterns of twos develop different intrinsic rhythmns than babies that get bounced in groups of 3s.


			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/tb303.png")
					figcaption
						small Roland TB303 Bassline Generator

				aside.notes
					p The Roland TB303 synthesiser contains an electronic filter that unintentionally mimics the distress cries of animals, where the instrument wails, shrieks and squeals - speaking to us on a primordial level, guided subconsciously by thousands of years of evolution in the wilderness, where we relied upon sound, which communicated with us before language.

					p This is the power of music - an innate language at the physiological level - you don’t just hear it, you feel it, you react to it. 

			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text Music is an unconscious exercise in mathematics in which the mind is unaware that it is calculating
					cite Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz

				aside.notes
					p Music affects us in profound ways, deeply in the neo-cortex, influencing your amygdola.
			
					p Before these modern times, it was not uncommon for a belief in the concept of the sound ether, one of the four stages in the creation of matter, where sound is crucial as the force that gives a substance its preliminary shape and form. 

					p Which sounds relatively similar to the Bose-Einstein condensate...

					p I mean
					
					p They didn’t call it the big bang because they thought it was silent!

					p I was approached by a Quantum physicist who wanted to explain to me that how without air, there could be no sound... 

			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text If a tree falls in a forest and no one is around to hear it, does it make a sound?
					
				aside.notes
					p whilst completely disregarding the fact that there could be no ears there to hear it.
			
			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text The record had grooves but no stylus was present.

				aside.notes
					p The record had grooves but no stylus was present.

					p Consider the Baryon Acoustic Oscillations.

					p Sound moves many magnitudes.

			section
				h4 FRISSON
				aside.notes
					p So, there is a hidden language that speaks directly to our brain, forged through millennia of evolution, directly influenced by our interactions with the world and the sounds that have guided us. 

					p This universal language can be used effectively to control moods and evoke emotions without a prior contract.

					p As music, it is a powerful tool that can directly affect your physiology. 

					p So, to represent a human using technology it must...

			section
				h3 Goal :
				p.r-fit-text Authentically represent intention through expression 
				aside.notes
					p Capture and authentically represent your expression.

					p What we need is some kind of way to simplify the complicated processes, to leverage automation and exploit the predictability of music and language.
			
			section
				h3 Practise, Practise!
				aside.notes
					p Most musical instruments don’t come easily.

					p So rather than requiring someone to alter their physical expression to work with an instrument, how about we alter the instrument to work with that person’s expressions?

					p A musical instrument that plays you?

					p What if we could make an instrument that converts your intrinsic intentions into auditory expressions?

					p Your moods into music?

					p It becomes so much easier to learn a physical skill when it is based on your natural movements, so that you can express yourself in the way that you feel most comfortable.

			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text Repetition serves as the handprint for human intent
					cite Elizabeth Hellmuth Margulis

				aside.notes.
					p Repetition is reassuring.

					p Repetition encourages humans to learn patterns.

			section
				h1 ?
				aside.notes
				
					p So... What would a musical instrument look like that uses you as the basis for a performance?

					p Well, we could use automation to provide the foundational structure and machine learning to extract our intentions, reflecting our expression through appropriate sounds. 

					p Sound directly inspired by you, where the music follows the dance.
										
					p Rather than using machines and automation to replace the act of creation - the playing of the game - we can instead use it to replace the process.


			section
				figure.full-size.wallpaper 
					img(src="/static/talk/dreamCapturer.png" alt="dreamCapturer - record your dreams")
					figcaption
						small dreamCapturer - Dream recorder © 2000 zenon olenski 
				
				aside.notes
					p This is a dreamCapturer, a machine that converts your dreams into music and tracks the soundtrack of your sleep.
					
					p Your entire performance happens unconsciously, unaware, silent and still, yet the music is vivid, compelling and full of expression and movement.

					p By converting biometrics and emotions into data, it is possible to analyse and extract the user's intention and mood. 
			
					//- p During sleep your vital statistics are being controlled by your central autonomous nervous system, regulated by your unconscious brain. You don’t have to think to breathe or blink - this is the domain of the autonomous nervous system.

			section
				figure.full-size.wallpaper
					video(data-autoplay, muted, src="/static/talk/photosynth.mp4")
					figcaption
						a(href="https://photosynth.lol") 
							small PhotoSYNTH : Smile Powered Synthesiser © 2020 zenon olenski 
		
				aside.notes
					p This is a Sympathetic Synthesizer, a smile powered pop music machine.
					
					p Without any musical skill you and your friends can make a full song using only your faces by converting your facial expressions, motions and moods into music. 

					p Smile for a happy sound, frown for malaise.

					p This magic mirror puts a smile on your face and makes it musical.
					
			//- section
			//- 	figure
			//- 		img(src="/static/talk/bowler_hat.jpg")
			//- 		figcaption
			//- 			small Magic Bowler Hat © 2010 Z. Olenski

			section
				h3 Automate
				aside.notes.
					Rather than compete with machines...

			section
				h3: strike Auto-mate
				h3 Auto-Friend
				aside.notes
					p Collaborate with them.
					
					p Befriend the robots. 
					
					p This unavoidable future looks set to radically empower human imagination with the boundless new medium of prompt engineering and digital materialisation. 

			section 
				figure 
					img(src="/static/talk/midi-genie-lamp.png")

				aside.notes
					p Like a wish-granting genie, you ask for an item that you would like, in as much detail as you care, and magically your desire momentarily manifests into reality. 

					strong [MAGIC]

					p In order to satisfy your request, the machine, having trained on the prior works of the entire species, uses probability to guess what the most likely output to satisfy your request would be by remixing them into derived works, extended from the foundations of those original human endeavours. 

					p Any derivative work is merely a prompt away.


			section 
				h3 OWNERSHIP
				figure.fragment.wallpaper.full-size 
					img(src="/static/talk/ai-space-scene.jpg")
					figcaption Personalised Media
				//- p Knowledge, governance, and legitimacy
				aside.notes
					p There are some beautiful things that come with this technology.

					p A friend of mine who used to sit watching TV in silence with his kids, now make their own show set in space, featuring their own characters, famous folk as well as friends and family. The kids work on the plot and draw designs for the characters and together they create something meaningful and memorable. 

					p I think that's a beautiful thing.

					p The beautiful thing here however, isn't the end product, it's the act of community, of collaboration, of human connection.

					p Their relationship is stronger due to quality of the time they spend together.

			section 
				blockquote
					p CREATING > CONSUMING

				aside.notes
					p When they started making the show they had their favourite famous characters intergrated into the plot.

					p Disney have other ideas, and sued the AI platforms until they removed their characters from derived works. These characters can no longer feature in AI generated materials due to these copyright claims.

					p They had employed the same legal strategy for decades, even changing copyright laws along the way. 

					p As this is personalised media created by individuals, with little intrinsic value to others, it is never shared widely or sold. 
					
					p It is considered a family memory, with more similarity to a family photo than a hollywood movie. 

					p Disney has no way to extract value once they are created.

					p Ultimately, this may reduce our desires for and depencies on those famous characters, as their relevance fades away through self-imposed obscurity.

					//- strong [CLICK]

					p You cannot use a single second of a song on Youtube without receiving a coyright claim, yet you can replicate entire discographies of artists with only subtle minor variations using machine learning and dodge copyright entirely.

					p Grey areas are merging together and copyright laws are falling apart.

					p Many of the companies who stole their training data and got sued have now partnered with the very people they stole from through some kind of magically effective Stockholm syndrome.

					p It has become an established way to launder copyright.



			section 
				h4.r-fit-text How many instructions does it require in order to own something?

				ol(role="list")
					li: p Create a happy pop song.

					li: p Create an uplifting synth-pop song. Use warm analog synthesizers, a slow drum-machine groove and a female vocal style inspired by 1980s dream pop. The arrangement should gradually become more layered and emotionally intense.

					li: p Create an inspirational and uplifting synth-pop composition in the key of A, called "Goblin Pigeon" using the chord progression Cm–Ab–Eb–Bb at 131 BPM. Restrict the arrangement to Dorian Mode and add harmonies to the melodies only by transposing the hook. The chorus should repeat the phrase ‘Gobble gobble goblin’. Clone and preserve the human quality of the provided reference female vocal performance.

				aside.notes
					p Is it possible to extract the exact point I became the author?

					p At what point can I consider this piece as my own?

					p It isnt related to the lengh or the complexity, or some kind of division of labour

					p At which point is ownership relenquished?

			section 
				h4.r-fit-text SOUL.MD

				aside.notes
				
					p can that essence itself be extracted?

					p can it be duplicated?
					p can it be replicated?

					p can the process be replicated?

					p Can we ever really own music? It is a bit like saying you own a smell.

					p Could we ever really own things before?


			// Slop cycle and Data
			section
				figure
					img(src="/static/talk/ai-slop-cycle-before.jpg")
					figcaption.
						The AI Slop Cycle

				aside.notes
					p If the genes in two human partners are too similar, they result in complications, as human DNA contains a mechanism to prevent inbreeding. 

					p Today, over a third of the internet is now AI generated. 
			
			section
				figure 
					img(src="/static/talk/Ouroboros.png")
					figcaption 
						small The machine will eat itself

				aside.notes
					p There are no mechanisms in place to protect AI from being trained on itself. 

					p Model inputs are being trained on model outputs... further weakening the pool

					p In a race to the bottom












