				aside.notes
					p In the early 1800s, nearby to Manchester -- birthplace of the industrial revolution, a group of disenfranchised textile workers, led by the enigmatic Ned Ludd, systematically destroyed the machinery that was brought in to increase productivity. 
					
					p The looms and mills were vandalised beyond the point of repair. This pushback or, "collective bargaining", was powerful, but it was not the technology that the Luddites disagreed with, but how it required more demanding labour for the same pay. 
					
					p The reduced price per product meant production had to exponentially increase. 

					p They were not anti-technology or anti-progress, they just required fair compensation

