						small Everything is fine...
				
				h5.fragment Take Action!
				ol(role="list").fragment
					li: p Always verify : Never believe anything a robot tells you
					li: p Don't expect a robot to have your best intentions at heart
					li: p: a(href="https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(26)00603-3/fulltext") Never let a robot write your references or citations
					li: p Remember robots lack nobility, integrity, pride and ethics
					li: p Don't mistake language for meaning
					li: p Don't allow one to talk for you
					li: p Prompting into an LLM is never a safe space
					li: p Making a pen that writes for you is not solving the correct problem
					li: p Never trust a robot with anything important
					li: p Human mimicry should not be confused for consciousness
					li: p Privacy and consent are more essential than ever
					li: p Never give an agent the keys to your house

				aside.notes
					p So how is everything? 
					p 
					strong [CLICK]
					strong [CLICK]
					strong [CLICK]
					p Everything is fine?


			section
				blockquote 
					p.r-fit-text Always remember you are allowed to do the opposite of what any AI suggests
					cite The golden rule

				aside.notes
					p These models homogenise data.
					p so the golden rule, 
					p if you want to make something fresh, do the opposite of what the AI thinks
					p Use AI tangentially

			section
				h5 What have we learned?
				ol(role="list")
					li: p Musical instruments pre-date Homosapiens and were a gift from Neanderthals  
					li: p Music can be entirely synthesised mathematically
					li: p Machine learning is great at figuring out patterns and trends
					li: p Robots can be trained to deconstruct and reconstruct music
					li: p Robots can perfectly clone voices and mimic sounds
					li: p Music affects people in ways they cannot control
					li: p Creativity is not unique to humans and is a skill that can be taught
					li: p People are resilient to change and to the unfamiliar
					li: p You will be mischaracterised in the future 
					li: p Data centres were not the answer to global warming
					li: p Secretly, compute costs are more expensive than employee salaries
					li: p Consciousness, like the human soul, probably doesn't exist
					li: p Centralising data in data centers is likely unneccessary.
					
				aside.notes
					p Machines arguably will create the wildest jazz, the heaviest Industrial, the catchiest pop and, perhaps most surprising of all, the most punk punk. 
					
					p A machine with no understanding of rhythm or tuning could theoretically even create a new Shaggs LP. 

					p I am hopeful.

			section
				//- h3 Takeaways
				h5 Unanswered questions
				ol(role="list")
					li: p Will we ever consider robot art as good as “human art?
					li: p Do we need the Music Defense League to return? 
					li: p Were the Luddites right all along about labour?
					li: p What can we believe when everything can be faked?
					li: p At what point in automation can you still claim ownership?
					li: p If an A.I. creates anything, even in collaboration, who ultimately owns the copyright?
					li: p When information becomes ubiquitous does it become worthless?

				aside.notes
					p I’ll leave you with some things to think about for yourself whilst you consider your life choices. 
					
					p Luckily, you are here at the right time.

